<html>
  <head>
    <title>Simultaneity</title>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>
      Simultaneity
    </h1>
    <p style="margin-top: 0">
      A <font color="#ff8000">wave source</font> and two equidistant <font color="#ff00ff">detectors</font> 
      are at rest in reference frame <font color="#008000"><i>S'</i></font>, 
      which moves with constant velocity <i>v </i>in frame <font color="#ff0000"><i>S</i></font>, 
      along the common axis <font color="#000080"><i>X</i></font>. Clocks are 
      synchronized so that at <font color="#ff0000"><i>t</i></font> = <font color="#008000"><i>t'</i></font> 
      = 0 the origins of coordinates coincide: <font color="#ff0000"><i>O</i></font> 
      = <font color="#008000"><i>O'</i></font>. At the same time a wave front 
      quits the source and is eventually detected. We consider two cases:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <b>Sound</b>: air is at rest in reference frame <font color="#008000"><i>S'</i></font>, 
        where the velocity of sound is <i>c</i>. Galilean relativity can be 
        used and we consider only the subsonic case <i>v</i> &lt; <i>c</i>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>Light</b>: <i>c</i> is the speed of light in vacuum and special 
        relativity must be used.
      </li>
    </ul>
